While I do have other units, I prefer my 650 for making top quality tournament grade loads OR take five minutes and adjust it to accept 3" or 3.5" shells and press out the perfect turkey, pheasant, duck, goose, dove or whatever other load you may need.  This will not only save you several dollars per box of ammo, but give you the satisfaction of having done it yourself.  The 650's versatility also allows you to load several boxes per hour for practicing clay target shooting!

The press is easy to use and understand, plus MEC has phenomenal customer service if you ever have a problem...they will walk you through whatever the issue is, no matter how big or small and will treat you with respect every time. 

Charge Bar, Powder Bushing and Manual are all included.

Sorry for the standard 'stock' photo, I will get one of the actual unit once I have time.  Thank you for looking.

VLTOR Basic IMod Clubfoot Milspec Stock - Black 

Improved Modstock, appropriately named the IMod. Since 2002, the original Modstock has become well known and respected by Military, Law-Enforcement and sports shooters worldwide. Even though the Modstock is considered the best on the market, Vltor believed it was time for improvements. The improvements are subtle but necessary. Feedback from end users will make the IMod the choice over the competition. 

When compared to the original Modstock, the IMod series is now available to fit either the Milspec or Commercial diameter receiver extension/buffer tube. Unfortunately, the IMod will not fit both receiver extensions, so when ordering, pick the correct item and part number. 

The improvements of the IMod are as follows: Integral, but removable non-slip buttpad (color matched to stock components) 

Rolled/angled buttpad toe with wide traction area. This will assist in running the stock high on shoulder, making the IMod system more user friendly when using web-gear and/or body armor. 
Improved lock paddle, making it easier to operate and making the contact surface non-slip when operating the lever. 
Removed most sharp edges that may cause snag points to web-gear or other vital equipment. 
Improved strength throughout construction of the stock chassis. This will provide maximum strength during Mortaring exercise or unexpected impact. 
Integral, but removable non-slip buttpad (color matched to stock components) 

Installation note: The installation of the IMod stock should only be performed by a qualified gunsmith and/or certified armorer. 

IMOD at a glance: Details 
Design Removable rubber buttpad and storage compartments. A true Modular buttstock for the AR15/M16/M4 carbine series. 
Construction Impact and temperature resistant polymer, specially blended for Vltor. Metal components are either carbon steel or stainless steel (depending on the application) 
Compatibility Milspec IMods will only fit receiver extensions/buffer tubes with the outer diameter of 1.150, while Commercial IMods will only fit 1.170 diameter receiver extensions. 
Weight - Nominal Less than 9.4 oz. (Milspec and Commercial with storage compartment and buttpad installed) 
Dimensions Length: 6.250 (without buttpad) 
Length: 6.626 (with buttpad) 
Width: 2.500 (with storage compartments installed)Height: 5.210 (with buttpad installed)

Color Finish All stocks have a matte (anti-reflection/glare) finish. IMods are only available in the following colors: Black, Flat Dark Earth (Tan) and Foliage Green. Foliage Green is more of a grey green versus Olive Drab. 
Special Features Storage capacity: Each side compartment can hold at least two AAs or three lithium CR123 3-volt batteries. The internal diameter of each compartment is 0.685. 

Sling mounting: All Modstocks, including the IMod will accept a push-button, quick detachable sling swivel or a conventional web sling, measuring up to 1.375 in width.

title: For Sale:  Tips on selling your gun successfully on armslist!
postcontent:
With this current rush of gun buying and selling, the internet is a great tool to sell your weapon. Here are some tips on how to do that effectively and not piss everyone off.

1) Realize that a savvy buyer is going to alt+tab and check both the MSRP and current going rate of your firearm on auction sites like gunbroker, gunsamerica, etc. Your glock 19 is not going to sell for $850 just because your local gunstore has it on backorder. Be reasonable.

2) Listing your firearm as "custom" because you tacked on some magpul or ncstar shit you bought from your local tacticool outfit is douchey. Custom is generally accepted to mean you built or had it custom built (i.e. barrel, reciever, wildcat chambering, etc) meaning you should probably name the gunsmith that did it or your own credentials at gunsmithing.

3) Associating your firearm with "special forces" or "navy seals" or " what they are using in afghanistan". You are probably wrong, these outfits change weapons continually as it suits them and there is no way in hell you are going to keep up on the trends unless you are a member. Plus its just douchey. No one cares that your grip-pod has been to afghanistan. You don't need to include that in the description.

4) current pictures. It is so easy to take a picture and post it, this is self explanatory.

5) Package deals. Making the asking price of your USED gun and all the USED crap that goes with it the msrp of all those items added together is stupid. Your customer can just go buy it all new and not deal with the inconvenience of arranging a meet.

6) "Im not necessarily looking to sell" or "i really dont want to sell this" WELL THEN WHY THE HELL HAVE YOU POSTED IT FOR SALE? This is a silly tactic that is somehow supposed to communicate that you love this gun so much, you are only going to take top dollar. It is a giant turn-off to buyers unless you have some badass 24k gold plated wildcat shit made by P.O. Ackley himself. WHICH YOU DON'T. So please spare us.

7) Trades. Look up the trade values, this is self explanatory. Your M&P 15 is not worth a straight trade for an M1A ebr. Your M1A Socom is not worth a LaRue OBR. Just add in the disclaimer that you are willing to add cash on your end, or look like a retard.

All this being said, 
WTB:

Any Flat-top A3 upper w/ 16" m4 barrel and low-pro gas block
Whitworth/Interarms mk X/Remington 798 in 30-06
Glock 20 or 21 Lower frame assy, Gen2/3 or RTF2
